Ay, my good lord.


Gerard de Narbon was my father;


In what he did profess, well found.

I must not hear thee; fare thee well, kind maid;


Thy pains not used must by thyself be paid:


Proffers not took reap thanks for their reward.

Yes, my good lord;
But never hope to know
why I should marry her.

I must tell thee, sirrah, I write man;
to which
title age cannot bring thee.

Yes, good faith, every dram of it;
and I will not
bate thee a scruple.

A good knave, i' faith, and well fed.


Madam, my lord will go away to-night;


A very serious business calls on him.


The great prerogative and rite of love,


Which, as your due, time claims, he does acknowledge;


But puts it off to a compell'd restraint;


Whose want, and whose delay, is strew'd with sweets,


Which they distil now in the curbed time,


To make the coming hour o'erflow with joy


And pleasure drown the brim.

Let that go:
My haste is very great: farewell;
hie home.

Something; and scarce so much: nothing, indeed.


I would not tell you what I would, my lord: Faith, yes;


Strangers and foes do sunder, and not kiss.

Welcome shall they be;


And all the honours that can fly from us


Shall on them settle. You know your places well;


When better fall, for your avails they fell:


To-morrow to the field. [Flourish.Exeunt.

Ay, madam;
And for the contents' sake are sorry
for our pains.

I prithee, lady, have a better cheer;


If thou engrossest all the griefs are thine,


Thou robb'st me of a moiety: he was my son;


But I do wash his name out of my blood,


And thou art all my child. Towards Florence is he?

Then go thou forth;


And fortune play upon thy prosperous helm,


As thy auspicious mistress!

I know not what the success will be,
my lord;
but the attempt I vow.

I should believe you;


For you have show'd me that which well approves


You're great in fortune,

You are undone, captain, all
but your scarf;
that has a knot on't yet.

I am no great Nebuchadnezzar, sir;
I have not
much skill in grass.

The black prince, sir; alias, the
prince of darkness;
alias, the devil.

With very much content, my lord;
and I wish
it happily effected.

'Tis past, my liege;


And I beseech your majesty to make it


Natural rebellion, done i' the blaze of youth;


When oil and fire, too strong for reason's

force,


O'erbears it and burns on.

If you shall marry,


You give away this hand, and that is mine;


You give away heaven's vows, and those are

mine;


You give away myself, which is known mine;


For I by vow am so embodied yours,


That she which marries you must marry me,


Either both or none.

Your reputation comes too short for
my daughter;
you are no husband for her.

I must be patient.


You, that have turn'd off a first so noble wife,


May justly diet me.   I pray you yet;


Since you lack virtue, I will lose a husband;


Send for your ring, I will return it home,


And give me mine again.

This woman's an easy glove, my lord;
she goes
off and on at pleasure.

Because he's guilty, and he is not guilty:


He knows I am no maid, and he'll swear to't;


I'll swear I am a maid, and he knows not.


Great king, I am no strumpet, by my life;


I am either maid, or else this old man's wife.

No, my good lord;


'Tis but the shadow of a wife you see.


The name and not the thing.
